## 1328 (2 Edw. 3)

The 4th Parliament of King Edward III, which met at Northampton from 24 April 1328 until 14 May 1328. This session was also traditionally cited as **2 Ed. 3** or **2 E. 3**.

### The [Statute of Northampton](/Statute_of_Northampton):
*   **c. 1 (Confirmation of charters)**: A confirmation of the Great Charter and the Charter of the Forest. Because some things bear repeating. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).
*   **c. 2 Pardons for Felony, Justices of Assize, etc. Act 1328** &#91;5&#93;: Outlined the specific cases in which a pardon for felony could be granted and who was eligible to serve as Justices of Assize. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision and Civil Procedure Act 1881](/Statute_Law_Revision_and_Civil_Procedure_Act_1881) ([44 & 45 Vict.](/44_%26_45_Vict.) c. 59) and for [Scotland](/Scotland) and [Northern Ireland](/Northern_Ireland) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1950](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1950) ([14 Geo. 6](/14_Geo._6). c. 6).
*   **c. 3 (Riding or going armed)**: A decree that no man shall appear before the Justices, nor travel about the realm, armed. An early, and apparently necessary, attempt to persuade the populace that legal disputes are best settled with arguments, not steel. — repealed by [Criminal Law Act 1967](/Criminal_Law_Act_1967) (c. 58).
*   **c. 4 (Sheriff)**: A confirmation of the Statute of Lincoln, which dealt with the sufficiency of sheriffs. — repealed by [Sheriffs Act 1887](/Sheriffs_Act_1887) ([50 & 51 Vict.](/50_%26_51_Vict.) c. 55).
*   **c. 5 (Sheriff)**: Detailed the proper manner for delivering writs to the sheriff for execution. — repealed by [Sheriffs Act 1887](/Sheriffs_Act_1887) ([50 & 51 Vict.](/50_%26_51_Vict.) c. 55).
*   **c. 6 (Confirmation of statutes, etc.)**: Granted justices the authority to punish breakers of the peace. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).
*   **c. 7 (Inquiry of past felons, etc.)**: Stated that commissions shall be granted to certain persons to hear and determine offences previously committed and to punish the offenders. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).
*   **c. 8 (Commands in delay of justice)**: Established that no command under the King's seal should disturb or delay justice. A principle easier stated than enforced. — repealed by the [Statute Law (Repeals) Act 1969](/Statute_Law_(Repeals)_Act_1969) (c. 52).
*   **c. 9 Staples Act 1328** &#91;6&#93;: Decreed that all staples (designated markets) shall cease, and all merchants may come and go with their merchandise. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).
*   **c. 10 (Pardon of fines)**: The King's pardon of forfeited fines. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).
*   **c. 11 (Common Bench)**: The common bench was not to be removed without warning by adjournment. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).
*   **c. 12 (Annexing Hundreds to Counties)**: Hundreds and Wapentakes were to be annexed to counties and not leased out to farm. — repealed by [Sheriffs Act 1887](/Sheriffs_Act_1887) ([50 & 51 Vict.](/50_%26_51_Vict.) c. 55).
*   **c. 13 (Process for Past Trespasses)**: Dealt with the process for trespasses committed during the time of King Edward II. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).
*   **c. 14 (Measure, etc. of Cloths Imported)**: Specified the measure and assize of cloths of ray and of colour. — repealed by [Woollen Manufacture Act 1809](/Woollen_Manufacture_Act_1809) ([49 Geo. 3](/49_Geo._3). c. 109).
*   **c. 15 [Keeping of Fairs Act 1328](/Keeping_of_Fairs_Act_1328)**: No person shall keep a fair longer than they are permitted to. — repealed by [Statute Law (Repeals) Act 1969](/Statute_Law_(Repeals)_Act_1969) (c. 52).
*   **c. 16 (Inquests)**: *Nisi prius* could be granted at the tenant's suit as well as the demandant's. — repealed by [Civil Procedure Acts Repeal Act 1879](/Civil_Procedure_Acts_Repeal_Act_1879) ([42 & 43 Vict.](/42_%26_43_Vict.) c. 59).
*   **c. 17 (Writs of deceit)**: A writ of deceit was maintainable in cases of garnishment in a plea of land. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).

