## 1330 (4 Edw. 3)

The 6th Parliament of King Edward III, which met at York from 11 March 1330 until 21 March 1330. This session was also traditionally cited as **4 Ed. 3** or **4 E. 3**.

*   **c. 1 (Confirmation of charters & statutes)**: A confirmation of all statutes not yet repealed. A legislative throat-clearing. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).
*   **c. 2 (Justices of assise & gaol delivery: justices of the peace)**: Outlined the authority of justices of Assize, Gaol-delivery, and of the Peace. — repealed by [Statute Law Revision and Civil Procedure Act 1881](/Statute_Law_Revision_and_Civil_Procedure_Act_1881) ([44 & 45 Vict.](/44_%26_45_Vict.) c. 59).
*   **c. 3 Civil Procedure Act 1330** &#91;7&#93; or **Purveyance Act 1330**: Regulated purveyors for the King, Queen, and their children, and what they were permitted to do. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).
*   **c. 4 (Purveyance)**: A confirmation of the statute 28 Edw. 1. Stat. 3. c. 2. &#91;a&#93; concerning purveyors. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).
*   **c. 5 (Pardon of fines, etc.)**: The King's pardon for certain fines and some money granted to him. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).
*   **c. 6 (Confirmation of 35 Edw. 1. Stat. Karl.)**: The statute made at Carlisle, Anno 35 Edw. 1. Stat. 1. &#91;b&#93; concerning religious persons, was confirmed. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).
*   **c. 7 (Executors' action for trespass)**: Granted executors the right to an action of trespass for a wrong done to their testator. — repealed by [Administration of Estates Act 1925](/Administration_of_Estates_Act_1925) ([15 & 16 Geo. 5](/15_%26_16_Geo._5). c. 23).
*   **c. 8 (Passages at the ports)**: At all passages, men were to pay no more for their fare than the customary rate. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Continuance, etc. of Laws Act 1623](/Continuance,_etc._of_Laws_Act_1623) ([21 Jas. 1](/21_Jas._1). c. 28) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law Revision (Ireland) Act 1872](/Statute_Law_Revision_(Ireland)_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).
*   **c. 9 (Hundred: Sheriff)**: Sheriffs, Bailiffs of Hundreds, and Escheators were required to have sufficient property in the county. — repealed by [Statute Law Revision and Civil Procedure Act 1881](/Statute_Law_Revision_and_Civil_Procedure_Act_1881) ([44 & 45 Vict.](/44_%26_45_Vict.) c. 59).
*   **c. 10 (Receipt of offenders by sheriffs, etc.)**: Sheriffs and gaolers were to receive offenders without taking anything for it. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).
*   **c. 11 (Justices of assize)**: Justices of Assize were to inquire of maintainers, conspirators, and champetors. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision and Civil Procedure Act 1881](/Statute_Law_Revision_and_Civil_Procedure_Act_1881) ([44 & 45 Vict.](/44_%26_45_Vict.) c. 59) and for [Scotland](/Scotland) and [Northern Ireland](/Northern_Ireland) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1950](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1950) ([14 Geo. 6](/14_Geo._6). c. 6).
*   **c. 12 (Assay, etc. of wines)**: Wines were to be assayed and sold at reasonable prices. A perpetually optimistic piece of legislation. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).
*   **c. 13 (Pardons)**: A confirmation of the Statute of 2 Edward 3. cap. 2. &#91;c&#93; concerning the granting of pardons. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).
*   **c. 14 (Parliament)**: A parliament shall be held once every year. Another optimistic piece of legislation. — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).
*   **c. 15 (Farming of hundreds by sheriffs)**: Sheriffs were to let their hundreds and wapentakes for the old ferm (rent). — repealed for [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) by [Statute Law Revision Act 1863](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1863) ([26 & 27 Vict.](/26_%26_27_Vict.) c. 125) and for [Ireland](/Ireland) by [Statute Law (Ireland) Revision Act 1872](/Statute_Law_(Ireland)_Revision_Act_1872) ([35 & 36 Vict.](/35_%26_36_Vict.) c. 98).

